[6] Mexico
Date: 27 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Publico [trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.publico.com.mx>

Official Alarm for Dengue in Puerto Vallarta
-----------------------------------------------
The Secretary of Health of Jalisco [state] is calling for urgent
intervention in Puerto Vallarta because actions so far have not been
adequate to control the dengue outbreak, indicating that 2007 is a
year of greater risk of dissemination of the disease.
The Director General of the Public Health Secretariat for Jalisco,
Gerardo Salvador Paredes Romero, confirmed that the 1st cases of
dengue in 2007 have been reported. Of a total of 109 people affected,
101 were from Puerto Vallarta, and of these, 20 had DHF.
As of last year [2006], Puerto Vallarta has been the municipality
most affected by dengue outbreaks. In 2006, 1107 cases were recorded
in this tourist destination (of a total of 1851 in the entire state
of Jalisco). Although there has been an intensification of [control]
actions, including fogging [with insecticides] of the municipality,
the official said, "This has not been sufficient to control the outbreak."
Beginning on Monday [29 Jan 2007] a "rapid response plan" will be
launched, with the participation of the federal Secretariat of
Health, the municipal government and with businesses. Paredes Romero
said that efforts will be redoubled and will proceed along 3 lines:
fogging [with insecticide] to kill adult [mosquitoes], use of abate
[larvacide] to eliminate breeding, and getting citizens to clean up
their patios and properties to avoid proliferation of new breeding
sites. Fogging in Puerto Vallarta and surrounding urban areas will
cover an area that includes 53 000 residences with a population of
220 000 inhabitants.
Implementation of this plan will cost 4 million pesos [USD 400 000]
and take a month, with weekly fogging.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is an example of how an epidemic disease, such as dengue,
potentially can have serious economic consequences in a popular
tourist destination, especially now, at the height of the tourist
season. Should dengue become a serious problem, once the word gets
out tourists will stay away in droves. ProMED will be very interested
to know how effective these vector control measures are, and wish the
state and federal health authorities success in controlling the
outbreak in a timely way.
A map of Mexico can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/mexico_pol97.jpg>.
WHO describes dengue fever as a severe, flu-like illness that affects
infants, young children, and adults but is seldom fatal. The clinical
features of dengue fever vary according to the age of the patient.
Infants and young children may have a non-specific febrile illness
with rash (although some infants and very young children may develop
shock syndrome, with sudden loss of circulating fluid volume, and
die). Older children and adults may have either a mild febrile
syndrome or the classical incapacitating disease, with abrupt onset
and high fever, severe headache, pain behind the eyes, muscle and
joint pains, and rash.
Dengue hemorrhagic fever is a potentially deadly complication that is
characterized by high fever, hemorrhagic phenomena -- often with
enlargement of the liver -- and in severe cases, circulatory failure.
The illness commonly begins with a sudden rise in temperature
accompanied by facial flush and other non-specific constitutional
symptoms of dengue fever. The fever usually continues for 2 to 7 days
and can be as high as 40-41 C (104-105.8 F), possibly with febrile
convulsions and hemorrhagic phenomena. In moderate DHF cases, all
signs and symptoms abate after the fever subsides. In severe cases,
the patient's condition may suddenly deteriorate after a few days of
fever; the temperature drops, followed by signs of circulatory
failure, and the patient may rapidly go into a critical state of
shock and die within 12-24 hours or quickly recover following
appropriate volume replacement therapy. There is no specific
treatment for dengue fever. However, careful clinical management by
experienced physicians and nurses frequently saves the lives of DHF
patients. With appropriate intensive supportive therapy, mortality
may be reduced to less than one per cent. Maintenance of the
circulating fluid volume is the central feature of DHF case
management. (Abstracted from the WHO website fact sheet on dengue:
<http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs117/en/>).
ProMED-mail thanks the contributors to this update and encourages
others to contribute reports also. - Mod.TY/JW]
[Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com> reminds us that a previous study
by Thai research workers identified dengue fever as a differential
diagnosis factor for H5N1 in children (See: Areechokchai D. et al.,
Investigation of avian influenza (H5N1) outbreak in humans--Thailand,
2004. MMWR, 55 Suppl 1: 3-6. 2006
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su5501a2.htm>).
-- see ProMED ref. below. - Mod.JW]
